  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">This dataset, deposited on Dryad in 2022 in support of biophysical simulations of primary visual cortex, has accumulated 361 views and 38 downloads, attracted 4 scholarly citations, and shows evidence of downstream reuse in at least 6 subsequent works \u2014 a modest but meaningful footprint for a specialized computational neuroscience resource.</p>\n\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The dataset underpins research into how neural circuit architecture generates the current sinks and sources observable in local field potential recordings from primary visual cortex. It is the product of a cross-institutional collaboration spanning the University of Oslo, the Norwegian University of Life Sciences, and the Allen Institute for Brain Science \u2014 bringing together computational modelers and experimental neuroscientists to bridge biophysical simulation with electrophysiological observation. The associated analysis code is publicly available via GitHub, reinforcing the transparency of the methodological pipeline.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Usage metrics recorded by Dryad indicate 361 views and 38 downloads, a pattern consistent with a technically specialized dataset that attracts a targeted audience of computational and systems neuroscientists rather than broad general interest. The dataset is openly accessible under a green open-access model, lowering barriers to reuse for researchers working in electrophysiology, neural modeling, and related fields.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Scholarly uptake, while early-stage, is substantive in context. The dataset has received 4 citations via OpenAlex, mirroring citation counts recorded for its associated preprint. More tellingly, the reuse graph identifies at least 6 downstream works that engage with this resource, including formal mentions in biomedical literature indexed by Europe PMC. Notably, an eLife article formally lists the dataset as supplementary material, and a PLOS Computational Biology article also references it \u2014 indicating that the data has already entered active circulation within the computational neuroscience community.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">No social media engagement or online event mentions were detected in the available monitoring period, which is typical for highly technical simulation datasets where uptake occurs primarily through specialist literature channels rather than public discourse. Taken together, the evidence suggests a dataset that is fulfilling its core function: enabling reproducibility and providing a foundation for further modeling work in cortical electrophysiology, even if its broader visibility remains limited at this stage.</p>",
